p.link: The Fed fine-tuned rate projections and announced more cuts in bond buyingCompany name that should showEND
The S&P 500 rose 14.99 points to a record 1956.98 on the Fed's outlook. The Dow gained 98.13 to 16906.62.
A House panel was subpoenaed for a probe into whether congressional staff helped tip off Wall Street traders to a health-care policy change.
GM officials ignored a 2005 warning about ignition-switch flaws, according to emails released by a House panel.
Auto-safety regulators are looking at Chrysler and Jeep vehicles for ignition-switch problems similar to GM's.
American Apparel's board moved to fire founder and CEO Charney, citing an investigation into alleged misconduct.
A federal agency withdrew trademark protection for the NFL's Redskins, saying the name insults Native Americans.
Amazon unveiled a smartphone with features that include software that can recognize merchandise.
Some funds that clashed over investments in Argentina are now in position to begin counting their winnings.
The IRS is boosting penalties on U.S. taxpayers who hide assets abroad, while cutting fines if a failure to disclose accounts is unintentional.
T-Mobile will waive data charges for music services, giving up potential revenue to bolster its subscriber base.
